# Build artifacts
dist/
build/
pkg/

# Oracle distributions. The binaries aren't ours to redistribute, so for each
# toolchain we ship a SHA-256 manifest (`BC2.sha256`, `MSC500.sha256`,
# `LATTICE*.sha256`) and a how-to-acquire doc (`BC2.md`, `MSC500.md`,
# `LATTICE*.md`) instead of the zip itself. The oracle crate lazily unpacks
# each zip into its own gitignored dir on first use. See
# specs/plans/SECOND_COMPILER.md and specs/PROVISIONING.md.
# The provisionable archives live beside their descriptors under oracles/<c>/;
# the rest (other compilers not yet on the provisioner) sit at the repo root.
oracles/**/*.zip
/BC*.zip
/MSC*.zip
/LATTICE*.zip
.bc2/
.msc500/
.lattice2/
.lattice3/
# `oracle provision <name>` media cache (downloaded 7z + unpacked floppy images).
.provision-*/

# Compiler binary build artifacts are NOT tracked. A fixture's
# `expected/<compiler>/<RELEASE>.toml` records the SHA-256 (and size) of every
# output, and that hash is the byte-exact contract the harness gates on. The
# multi-megabyte `.OBJ`/`.ASM`/`.EXE`/`.MAP` bytes plus captured `stdout`/`stderr`
# are a reproducible cache: regenerate them on demand with `xfix materialize
# <fixture>`, which re-runs the oracle and asserts each reproduction matches the
# recorded hash. They live under `artifacts/`, mirroring the fixtures tree
# (`artifacts/<fixture-path>/<compiler>/<RELEASE>/`), so git prunes the whole
# cache in one step instead of walking every fixture directory. See
# artifacts/README.md. They were purged from history once (see git log); never
# re-add them.
# `/artifacts/*` (not `/artifacts/`) so the README stays trackable while git
# still prunes each ignored subtree (artifacts/c/…) without descending into it.
/artifacts/*
!/artifacts/README.md

# Stray Borland-built artifacts at the repo root and the `w/` scratch dir.
/*.OBJ
/*.obj
/*.EXE
/*.exe
/*.MAP
/*.map
/*.ASM
/*.asm
/w/*.OBJ
/w/*.obj
/w/*.EXE
/w/*.exe

